KW  - MODELS
AB  - Projections indicate a high-risk water stress level (+80%) in the Western Cape province of South Africa by 2040. The reassessment of water management is paramount in ensuring water security for the generations to come. Water management approach, which recognizes the value of alternative water sources such as Urban Wastewater recycling (UWWR) amid shrinking surface water supplies is of critical importance. This management process mimics natural systems, placing the focus on stakeholder engagement and meaningful public participation. The objective is to ensure a vibrant economy, social equity, and protection of water resources for current and future generations. This paper's main goal is the assessment of the impact of UWWR on water availability in the Stellenbosch urban water system. Vensim PLE7.2 systems dynamic modeling tools constructed the qualitative and quantitative systems dynamics models. The results from the simulation indicated that UWWR in Stellenbosch has a significant potential of augmenting water supplies over a period of ten years. Of the three scenarios investigated, the 50% reuse scenario projected the best option for augmenting water supplies. In addition, results extrapolated from availability index graphs, depicted a water availability index, which is greater than 1 for every UWWR scenario investigated, i.e., 10%, 30%, and 50%, a positive result which supports the decision for UWWR in Stellenbosch as a water augmentation option.
