AB  - This study examines the challenge of balancing water and energy resources in Jatropha-based biodiesel production in arid regions. Although the water-energy nexus (WE) has been widely studied, its specific dynamics in Jatropha-based biodiesel production in water-stressed areas are less understood. To address this issue, an innovative system dynamics (SD) approach was designed using VENSIM software, leading to the creation of an integrated SD-WE nexus model. This model utilizes causal loops and flow diagrams to simulate interactions among the water, energy, and biodiesel subsystems. Scenario analysis indicates that conventional biodiesel production could reduce water resources by 32 to 63% and consume up to 14 billion cubic meters of water. However, the Bioshare scenario, which optimizes bioenergy production, reduces water consumption and maintains groundwater sustainability. The model has been validated through sensitivity analysis and data comparison, highlighting the urgent need for reforms in water management within Iran's energy sector. The SD-WE framework serves as a versatile tool for scenario testing, ensuring that biodiesel development aligns with water and energy security for sustainable policymaking.
