AB  - This research developed a sophisticated simulation-optimization model using a system dynamics (SD) approach integrated with MATLAB Simulink, targeting eutrophication management in dam reservoirs. Eutrophication, marked by overgrowth of algae due to nutrient excess, is a significant threat to water quality in these systems, with the Karkheh Dam reservoir in Iran serving as the focal case study. To capture the dynamics of eutrophication, the reservoir was divided into three vertical layers, facilitating a nuanced analysis of thermal stratification's effects on nutrient and dissolved oxygen distribution. Mathematical relationships pertinent to key eutrophication indicators-phosphorus, nitrogen, and dissolved oxygen concentrations-were meticulously developed for each layer, culminating in a comprehensive SD model. The model's outputs were compared against two established frameworks, Vensim and CE-QUAL-W2, over one year, employing statistical metrics such as Root Mean Square Error (RMSE) and correlation coefficients to assess accuracy. The Simulink model demonstrated superior predictive performance, particularly regarding chlorophyll-a and dissolved oxygen levels. Further, integrating a genetic algorithm (GA) with the SD model led to a GA-Simulink model, optimizing water release strategies over 15 years. This model operated 29 times faster than GA-CE-QUAL-W2, underscoring its effectiveness for efficient environmental management in reservoir systems.
