AB  - The increasing penetration of distributed energy resources in the residential sector, including photovoltaic generation (PV), electric vehicles (EV), and battery energy storage systems, has significantly altered electricity consumption patterns and introduced new challenges for energy management. These technologies, combined with time-of-use (TOU) tariffs, require analytical tools capable of representing the dynamic interactions among consumption, generation, storage, and tariff structures. This paper proposes a modular simulation model based on System Dynamics to evaluate residential electricity consumption, energy costs, and demand profile under different technological configurations and demand-side management (DSM) strategies. The model was implemented in Vensim and integrates residential load profiles, PV generation based on peak sun hours, EV charging schedules, behind-the-meter battery storage, and both flat and TOU tariffs. DSM strategies based on load shifting were incorporated to evaluate their impact on cost reduction and system performance. Simulation results demonstrate that the effectiveness of TOU tariffs strongly depends on load management strategies and the coordination between PV generation and battery storage. In the most complete scenario, DSM reduced the discounted payback period from approximately 6.0 years to 4.7 years under time-of-use tariffs, representing an improvement of 1.3 years. The proposed model provides a flexible and integrated framework for analyzing residential energy systems and supports decision-making related to distributed energy resource integration and tariff selection.
